snippet.textDisplay:
I'm a Chinese from Wuhan, I hope anyone who reads this circulate my blog link and message widely - all major metropolitan cities around the globe need to immediately set up 1000-bed makeshift hospitals that accommodate coronavirus carriers (including asymptomatic and suspected cases) to prevent more healthy people from being infected. Don't let those mild/asymptomatic virus carriers off home because they will infect their family members if they don't live alone. The coronavirus has long incubation period (can be up to 24 days, before people realise they are infected), and long therapeutic period (which means occupation of the hospital resources for too long/per patient in hospitals). Mild-severe patients will soon flood hospitals needing some level of medical intervention, but hospital beds won't be enough in any metropolitan city. Korea/Italy are both already experiencing tsunami of incoming COVID-19 patients in hospitals, which is exactly what Wuhan hospitals started to experience in mid-January until recently, a month after Jan 23 Wuhan lock-down. If these mild to mid-severe patients can't be treated in time by professionals, many of them will develop into severe-critical condition patients, and may die within 4 weeks, although they could be saved if medical intervention had come available earlier in their illness development. Too many tragedies like this happened in Wuhan, even to people in their 30th and 40th who eventually developed into critical condition stage, when freed-up hospital beds came too late. 

The official estimate is that almost 15% of identified symptomatic patients require oxygen support. The proportion of asymptomatic people that do not develop symptoms remains unclear. When the denominator of 'symptomatic patients' becomes too large, standard hospitals can't cope to deal with oxygen support demand, especially when every patient is infectious, requiring stringent standard of protection on the part of medical personnel and hospital wards.

The only effective measure to stem the spread of the virus, and to lessen pressure on public health infrastructure is to tirelessly identify anyone who may have been infected (adding the result of Computed Tomography Scan showing lungs infection images into clinical diagnostic criteria to aid diagnosis, relying solely on virus test lab results could be misleading and wrongly releasing virus carriers into society, which in turn seed the possibility of more people getting infected), isolate them into quarantine locations stringently and immediately. This is the only way to reduce the amount of people that may die caused by lack of medical resources, before a miracle cure comes to the rescue. Otherwise the death rate of the COVID-19 will be far higher than 2%. The reported death numbers in Wuhan is result of under-detection. There are known instances of people died of the infection at home without ever having the chance to be treated in a hospital. No one knows the real number of how many people died over the past month in Wuhan.

For more observations on the hard lessons learned by Wuhaners, please visit my blog https://covid19-wuhaner-info.blogspot.com
